## 3. Core Engine Integration & IP Protection

### 3.1 WASM vs. Backend Microservices — Definitive Comparison

| Criterion | WebAssembly (Client) | Backend Microservices (Server) | **Verdict** |
|---|---|---|---|
| **IP Protection** | ❌ WASM is decompilable; algorithms exposed in browser DevTools | ✅ Code never leaves your servers | **Server wins** |
| **Performance** | ⚠️ Must rewrite Python → Rust/C++; WASM is single-threaded | ✅ Scale horizontally with worker pods | **Server wins** |
| **Porting Effort** | ❌ Complete rewrite of 2400 lines + ReportLab + Pandas | ✅ Python stays Python; wrap with FastAPI | **Server wins** |
| **Latency** | ✅ Zero network round-trip | ⚠️ 1-5s for generation + download | **Client wins** |
| **Offline Support** | ✅ Works offline | ❌ Requires connection | **Client wins** |
| **Scalability Cost** | ✅ User's device = free compute | ⚠️ You pay for server compute | **Client wins** |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Recommendation: Server-side execution via containerized FastAPI microservices.**
>
> Your algorithms (MaxRects BSSF, chip-load tables, 4-op G-code pipeline) are your core IP. WASM would expose them to anyone with browser DevTools. Additionally, your codebase has Python-only dependencies (ReportLab for PDFs, Pandas for Excel) that have no WASM equivalents — a rewrite would take 3-6 months before you could even start the SaaS.

### 3.2 IP Protection Strategy

```mermaid
graph LR
    A[User Browser] -->|"JSON: parts + params"| B[API Gateway]
    B -->|Rate-limited / Authenticated| C[G-code Worker]
    C -->|"Runs proprietary Python"| D[Generated .nc file]
    D -->|Stored in| E[S3 with signed URLs]
    E -->|"Temporary link (1hr expiry)"| A
```

**Multi-layer protection:**

| Layer | Mechanism |
|---|---|
| **Network** | API Gateway with JWT auth; no unauthenticated access to generation endpoints |
| **Code** | Proprietary Python runs inside private Docker containers; no source code shipped to client |
| **Output** | G-code files stored in S3 with time-limited signed URLs (1-hour expiry) |
| **Rate Limiting** | Per-user quotas: Free = 5 gen/day, Pro = unlimited, Enterprise = custom |
| **Obfuscation** | Optional: PyArmor or Cython compilation of [.py](file:///home/victor/Documents/Work/SuperShaker/SuperShaker_v5.4.2.py) → `.so` inside Docker images |
| **Legal** | Terms of Service prohibiting reverse-engineering; DMCA takedown procedures |

### 3.3 Refactoring for Server Deployment

Your current code is tightly coupled to Tkinter (`tk.StringVar`, `messagebox`, `filedialog`). The refactoring strategy:

```
Current: AdvancedNestingGUI (monolith, 2439 lines)
    ├── UI layer (Tkinter) ─────────────── DISCARD for web
    ├── Core algorithms ─────────────────── EXTRACT as library
    │   ├── MaxRectsPacker ──────────────── nesting_engine.py
    │   ├── calc_t6_params ──────────────── chipload_calculator.py
    │   ├── generate_gcode (4 ops) ──────── gcode_generator.py
    │   ├── do_nesting ──────────────────── nesting_engine.py
    │   └── _sanitize_gcode ─────────────── gcode_generator.py
    └── Export (PDF) ────────────────────── pdf_export.py
```

**Step 1:** Extract a pure-Python library (`supershaker_core/`) with zero Tkinter dependencies:

```
supershaker_core/
├── __init__.py
├── nesting.py          # MaxRectsPacker + do_nesting logic
├── chipload.py         # calc_t6_params (static method → pure function)
├── gcode_generator.py  # generate_gcode (accepts dicts, returns list[str])
├── pdf_export.py       # PDF label + cutting map generation
├── models.py           # Pydantic models: Part, Sheet, ToolConfig, NestingResult
└── sanitizer.py        # _sanitize_gcode
```

**Step 2:** Wrap with FastAPI endpoints that accept JSON and return files/JSON.

