## 4. High-Performance Frontend & 3D Visualization

### 4.1 Frontend Stack

| Layer | Technology | Justification |
|---|---|---|
| **Framework** | **React 18+** with TypeScript | Largest ecosystem; best for complex state; huge hiring pool |
| **State Management** | **Zustand** | Lightweight; no boilerplate; perfect for CAM state (tool profiles, sheet configs, project trees) |
| **UI Components** | **Radix UI** + custom CSS | Accessible primitives, no design tax; CAM UIs are highly custom |
| **Form Handling** | **React Hook Form** + Zod | Type-safe validation for machine configs, numeric params |
| **Data Fetching** | **TanStack Query** | Caching, background refetch, optimistic updates for projects |
| **File Handling** | **tus** (resumable uploads) | Large CAD files need resumable upload support |
| **Build Tool** | **Vite** | Fast HMR; native ESM; optimal for iterating on complex UI |

### 4.2 3D Visualization Architecture — Three.js

> [!CAUTION]
> Your current Plotly Scatter3D approach **will not scale** to millions of G-code lines in a browser. Plotly creates individual DOM-backed traces — at 1M points, the browser will freeze. You need raw WebGL via Three.js.

**Architecture for handling large toolpaths:**

```mermaid
graph TB
    subgraph "Main Thread"
        REACT[React Component]
        THREE[Three.js Scene]
        CONTROLS[OrbitControls]
        LOD[LOD Manager]
    end

    subgraph "Web Worker"
        PARSER[G-code Parser Worker]
        SIMPLIFY[Douglas-Peucker Simplifier]
        BUFFER[Float32Array Builder]
    end

    subgraph "GPU"
        VBO[Vertex Buffer Objects]
        SHADER[Custom Line Shader]
    end

    REACT -->|"File ArrayBuffer"| PARSER
    PARSER -->|"Parsed segments"| SIMPLIFY
    SIMPLIFY -->|"Multi-LOD buffers"| BUFFER
    BUFFER -->|"transferable"| THREE
    THREE --> LOD
    LOD --> VBO
    VBO --> SHADER
    CONTROLS --> THREE
```

**Key techniques for millions of lines:**

| Technique | Purpose | Implementation |
|---|---|---|
| **Web Worker parsing** | Keep main thread responsive during G-code parse | `new Worker()` with `Transferable` ArrayBuffers |
| **Instanced BufferGeometry** | Single draw call for all lines of same type | `THREE.InstancedBufferGeometry` with per-instance color |
| **Level of Detail (LOD)** | Render simplified geometry when zoomed out | Douglas-Peucker algorithm at 3 levels (full / 50% / 10%) |
| **Frustum Culling** | Skip off-screen geometry | Built into Three.js; split toolpath into spatial chunks |
| **Streaming parse** | Start rendering before file fully loads | Parse in 64KB chunks, append to BufferGeometry |
| **GPU-side lines** | Fat lines that don't alias | `THREE.Line2` from `three/examples` (screen-space width) |

**Performance targets:**

| Metric | Target | Strategy |
|---|---|---|
| 1M G-code lines | < 2s parse + render | Web Worker + streaming BufferGeometry |
| 5M G-code lines | < 8s parse, 60fps orbit | LOD + frustum culling + chunked geometry |
| 10M+ G-code lines | < 15s parse, 30fps orbit | Progressive streaming + aggressive LOD |

