## 10. Top 3 Technical Bottlenecks & Mitigations

### Bottleneck #1: Core Engine Refactoring (Tkinter Decoupling)

> **Risk Level: HIGH** — This blocks everything else.

**Problem:** Your 2,439-line [SuperShaker_v5.4.2.py](file:///home/victor/Documents/Work/SuperShaker/SuperShaker_v5.4.2.py) reads parameters from `tk.StringVar` objects, calls `messagebox` for errors, and uses `filedialog` for I/O. The G-code generator is a single 800-line method with deeply nested control flow.

**Mitigation:**

| Step | Action | Time |
|---|---|---|
| 1 | Create Pydantic models for all inputs (`SheetConfig`, `FacadeParams`, `ToolConfig`, `Part`) | 2 days |
| 2 | Extract [MaxRectsPacker](file:///home/victor/Documents/Work/SuperShaker/SuperShaker_v5.4.2.py#14-93) → `nesting.py` (already a clean class, minimal changes) | 1 day |
| 3 | Extract [calc_t6_params](file:///home/victor/Documents/Work/SuperShaker/SuperShaker_v5.4.2.py#229-345) → `chipload.py` (already `@staticmethod`, trivial) | 0.5 days |
| 4 | Extract [generate_gcode](file:///home/victor/Documents/Work/SuperShaker/SuperShaker_v5.4.2.py#1643-2434) → `gcode_generator.py` (hardest: replace all `self._fval()` with function params) | 5 days |
| 5 | Extract [do_nesting](file:///home/victor/Documents/Work/SuperShaker/SuperShaker_v5.4.2.py#1151-1239) → pass flat part list + config, return `NestingResult` | 2 days |
| 6 | Write comparison tests: run desktop app + new lib on same inputs, assert identical output | 3 days |

> [!WARNING]
> **Do not optimize or refactor the algorithms during extraction.** Port them character-for-character. Optimization comes later. Every divergence from the original is a potential bug in G-code output — and bad G-code can crash a CNC machine.

### Bottleneck #2: 3D Viewer Performance at Scale

> **Risk Level: MEDIUM** — Impacts Pro/Enterprise user experience.

**Problem:** A single facade sheet can generate 50K–200K lines of G-code. A full production run (10+ sheets) easily hits 1M+ lines. Rendering this in a browser without frame drops requires careful engineering.

**Mitigation:**

| Technique | Impact | Implementation Effort |
|---|---|---|
| Web Worker G-code parsing | Prevents UI freeze during parse | Low (standard Web Worker API) |
| `Float32Array` + `Transferable` | Zero-copy transfer from worker → main thread | Low |
| `THREE.BufferGeometry` with `THREE.LineSegments` | Single draw call per tool | Medium |
| Spatial chunking (octree) | Only render visible toolpath chunks | Medium |
| LOD with Douglas-Peucker simplification | 3 detail levels based on camera distance | Medium |
| WebGPU fallback (future) | 2-5x performance over WebGL for complex scenes | High (experimental) |

**Performance test plan:** Generate a synthetic 5M-line G-code file; benchmark parse time, first-paint time, and orbit FPS on mid-range hardware (Intel i5 + integrated GPU).

### Bottleneck #3: Billing-Gated Feature Enforcement

> **Risk Level: MEDIUM** — Revenue leakage if implemented incorrectly.

**Problem:** Feature gating in a SaaS with a thick client is tricky. Users could:
- Inspect network requests and call API endpoints directly (bypassing UI gate)
- Cache Pro-tier responses and replay them after downgrade
- Share accounts across team members

**Mitigation:**

| Vector | Defense |
|---|---|
| **API bypass** | All feature gates enforced server-side (not just UI); middleware checks tier before executing |
| **Cached responses** | G-code files in S3 have 1-hour signed URL expiry; nesting results are user-scoped |
| **Account sharing** | Concurrent session limit: Free = 1, Pro = 3, Enterprise = unlimited; enforce via Redis session tracking |
| **Tier downgrade** | Cron job: after downgrade, don't delete data but gate access; "upgrade to view" prompt |
| **Webhook reliability** | Stripe webhook handler with idempotency keys + dead-letter queue for failed events |

